&lt;your quote edited by me for brevity&gt;
<br />

<br />
So it's different to camp a completely greened-out zone for cash?   Risk is next to nil, and large amounts of cash can be made, the only difference being that instead of sitting at a vendor, I'm killing truckloads of greens?
<br />
(This is aside from the issue of higher level PC's camping a zone which lower-level ones might want to use.)   I don't buy that in the slightest.
<br />

<br />
Sure, what I was doing was risk-free (if you don't count the times that I accidentally autoattacked the vendors and was wiped from the face of Norrath), however it was also very time- and wrist-intensive.   I quickly became tired of doing it for any more than a little quick cash when I was running low.   It did, however, allow me to fund the six (yes, six) final combines I needed to do at maxed skill with geerlok to finally get my trophy.
<br />

<br />
And to extend the discussion in the post you referenced, I'm curious to know if combines can be macroed.  I don't want to know how, as that might interfere with Sony's ability to prevent such things happening; I just want to know if it can be done.   I find it hard to believe that such a thing is even possible being that combines and buying/selling absolutely require mouse work (as far as I know, anyway), and I am unaware of programs which could automate that.   Being a sometime programmer, I can see a possible though very difficult-to-maintain way to do so.   The effort involved in creating the program which would do this would be just about as much as carpal-tunneling yourself doing the buying, combines, and selling.
<br />

<br />
Unless/until I find an answer in the positive, I find it difficult to believe that the change was made to prevent macroing millions of plat.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />Grimbul Garnet
<br />
Intrepid Gnomey Enchanter
